Solution:

The FP-Growth Algorithm is an efficient and scalable method for mining the complete set of frequent patterns by pattern fragment growth, using an extended prefix-tree structure for storing compressed and crucial information about frequent patterns named frequent-pattern tree.

Exercise 3

Generate 10,000 random examples of different contingency tables such that in the 2x2 contingency table values are at least 50 in each of the four cells and that all four values add up to 10,000 (i.e. are example 2x2 tables for a database of size 10,000 transactions). Generate the values in the way that only one value of 4 is “small” (between 50-99), any combination of two are “small”, any combination of 3 are “small” and all four are “large”. Try to cover the range of all possible 2x2 values quite evenly. Describe your idea and procedure clearly. And visualize the generated data. Note that fourth value is dependent (10,000 - sum_of_three), so you need to visualize only three values and leave for example the f11 visualized.

Solution:

For the generation of the random data I am using the sample function in R which generates random numbers from the range between \(1\) and \(10000\). The random numbers are normalized and multiplied by \(10000\) so their sum is set to be exactly \(10000\).

props2 <- function(nrow, ncol) {
    p <- function(n) {
        x1 <- sample(1:10000, ncol)
        vec <- round((x1/sum(x1)) * 10000)
        if (sum(vec) != 10000) {
            o <- diff(c(10000, sum(vec)))
            vec[which.max(vec)] <- max(vec) - o
        }
        return(vec)
    }
    DF <- data.frame(t(replicate(nrow, p(n = ncol))))
    return(DF)
}

We can check if the function is working first by inspecting the first \(10\) rows of the data set.

Exercise 4

Based on this synthetic data identify three best examples using lift, odds ratio and correlation measures. Explain them - what would the corresponding rules mean in the sense of supermarket shopping basket analysis (provide some scenario and example based on that).

Solution:

We are assuming that the contingency table has the following form:

We can add additional columns corresponding to the lift, odds ration and the correlation measures.

# Add odds ratio column
for (i in 1:nrow(DF)) {
    row <- DF[i, ]
    odds = round((DF[, 1] * DF[, 4])/(DF[, 2] * DF[, 3]))
    DF$odds = odds
}

# Add correlation column
for (i in 1:nrow(DF)) {
    row <- DF[i, ]
    phi = (DF[, 1] * DF[, 4])/(DF[, 2] * DF[, 3])/(sqrt(10000 * 10000))
    DF$phi = phi
}

# Add lift value for the rule X2 -> X1;
for (i in 1:nrow(DF)) {
    row <- DF[i, ]
    liftX2_X1 = (10000 * DF[, 1])/((DF[, 1] + DF[, 2]) * (DF[, 1] + DF[, 3]))
    DF$liftX2_X1 = liftX2_X1
}

# Add lift value for the rule X2 -> nX1; Similarly is done for the remaining
# two rules;
for (i in 1:nrow(DF)) {
    row <- DF[i, ]
    liftX2_nX1 = (10000 * DF[, 2])/((DF[, 1] + DF[, 2]) * (DF[, 2] + DF[, 4]))
    DF$liftX2_nX1 = liftX2_nX1
}

Exercise 6

Describe the measure Mutual Information. Report the rules with highest mutual information from synthetic data (3) and the Titanic data sets. Which association rules would have highest mutual information?

Solution:

Mutual information is one of many quantities that measures how much one random variables tells us about another. It is a dimensionless quantity with (generally) units of bits, and can be thought of as the reduction in uncertainty about one random variable given knowledge of another. High mutual information indicates a large reduction in uncertainty; low mutual information indicates a small reduction; and zero mutual information between two random variables means the variables are independent. Mutual information is a symmetric quantity.

The most common unit for MI is bits. In that case we measure show many bits will we need in order to store the outcomes Y given that you know the value of X. We can calculate the mutual information in bits using:

library(entropy)

# MI for the rules in the synthetic data
y1d = rbind(c(4368, 31), c(15, 5446))
mi1 = mi.empirical(y1d, unit = c("log2"))
mi1
## [1] 0.9489707
y2d = rbind(c(7351, 12), c(513, 2124))
mi2 = mi.empirical(y2d, unit = c("log2"))
mi2
## [1] 0.548008
y3d = rbind(c(3292, 3339), c(47, 3322))
mi3 = mi.empirical(y3d, unit = c("log2"))
mi3
## [1] 0.2200838

We can see that y3d has the lowest value which implies that the random variables in this case are most similar and we need the smallest amount of bits to represent them.

If we find the mutual information for the Titanic data set rules:

t1d = rbind(c(344, 126), c(367, 1364))
mi_t1 = mi.empirical(t1d, unit = c("log2"))
mi_t1
## [1] 0.1423912
t2d = rbind(c(57, 52), c(654, 1438))
mi_t2 = mi.empirical(t2d, unit = c("log2"))
mi_t2
## [1] 0.006410718

For the both cases we get mutual information that is close to 0 which means that knowing one of the features can helps us to determine the other.
